				<exercises>


 					<p><exercise>
 						<statement>
 							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 5, Exercise 5.1.2)</p></aside>
 							In each case, determine if <m>\vec{x}</m> is in <m>\span(\vec{y}, \vec{z})</m>.  If it is, write <m>\vec{x}</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vec{y}</m> and <m>\vec{z}</m>.  If not, explain why not.
 							<ol>
 								<li><m>\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\-1\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}, \vec{y} = \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}, \vec{z} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
 								<li><m>\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 2 \\ 15 \\ 11\end{bmatrix}, \vec{y} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\-1\\0\\2\end{bmatrix}, \vec{z} = \begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\\-3\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
 								<li><m>\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix}8\\3\\-13\\20\end{bmatrix}, \vec{y} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\-3\\5\end{bmatrix}, \vec{z} = \begin{bmatrix}-1\\0\\2\\-3\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
 								<li><m>\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\5\\8\\3\end{bmatrix}, \vec{y} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\-1\\0\\5\end{bmatrix}, \vec{z} = \begin{bmatrix}-1\\2\\2\\-3\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
 							</ol>
 						</statement>
 					</exercise></p>



 					<p><exercise>
 					<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 5, Exercise 5.1.3) </p></aside>
							In each case determine if the given vectors span all of <m>\mathbb{R}^4</m>.  Support your answer.
							<ol>
								<li><m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
								<li><m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\3\\-5\\0\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}-2\\1\\0\\0\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\2\\1\\-1\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}1\\-4\\5\\0\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
							</ol>
					</statement>
					<answer>
						<p> (a) Yes (b) No. </p>
					</answer>
 					</exercise></p>

 					<p><exercise>
 						<statement>
 							<aside><p> (Source: None)</p></aside>
 							Suppose that <m>\vec{v}, \vec{w}, \vec{z}</m> are vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, and <m>2\vec{v}</m> is in <m>\span(\vec{w}, \vec{z})</m>.  Show that <m>\span(\vec{v}, \vec{w}, \vec{z}) = \span(\vec{w}, \vec{z})</m>.
 						</statement>
 						<hint>
 							<xref ref="thm-span-unchanged-removal" /> is very helpful, but you need to do a little bit of work before you can apply it.
 						</hint>
 						<solution>
 							By definition of <m>2\vec{v}</m> being in <m>\span(\vec{w}, \vec{z})</m>, there are scalars <m>a, b</m> such that <me>2\vec{v} = a\vec{w} + b\vec{z}</me>.  Therefore <me>\vec{v} = \frac{a}{2}\vec{w} + \frac{b}{2}\vec{z}</me>, so <m>\vec{v}</m> is in <m>\span(\vec{w}, \vec{z})</m>.  Therefore <m>\span(\vec{v}, \vec{w}, \vec{z}) = \span(\vec{w}, \vec{z})</m> by <xref ref="thm-span-unchanged-removal" />.
 						</solution>
 					</exercise></p>

 					<p><exercise>
 						<statement>
 							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 4, Exercise 4.10.3)</p></aside>
 							Describe <m>\span\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-2\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}1\\3\\-2\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\\-2\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}-1\\0\\2\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}1\\3\\-1\end{bmatrix}\right)</m> using as few vectors as possible.
 						</statement>
 						<hint>
 							<xref ref="thm-span-unchanged-removal" /> will let you determine when you can remove one vector without changing the span, and then you can repeat that process until you can't remove anymore.
 						</hint>
 					</exercise></p>

 					<p><exercise>
 						<statement>
 							<aside> (Source: None) </aside>
 							What kind of geometric object is <m>\span\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\\-3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\\-7\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}5\\3\\6\end{bmatrix}\right)</m>?  Justify your answer.
 						</statement>
 						<answer>
 							A plane.
 						</answer>
 						<hint>
 							Use the definition of span to find out what conditions on <m>x, y, z</m> are necessary for <m>\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix}</m> to be in the span of the given vectors.
 						</hint>
 					</exercise></p>
				</exercises>
		